courses.learning_outcomes:
By the end of the course, students are expected to:
1. Demonstrate an understanding of the major concepts of a wide range of approaches to counseling theory and practice;
2. Analyze a case based on theoretical frameworks;
3. Possess an understanding of the techniques employed by different counseling orientations;
4. Identify important counselor attitudes and values that prepare a professional to work with clients with diverse problems and goals; and
5. Gain some initial ideas in constructing a personalized approach to counseling by integrating concepts and techniques from various theoretical orientations.

(Individual course teachers may update the learning outcome as and whenever necessary.)

Upon completion of this course, students are expected to be able to:

1. demonstrate an understanding of key concepts of group counselling theories and practice;
2. appreciate and recognize the therapeutic factors and dynamics of group counselling through experiencing as a group member and as a group leader;
3. master basic group facilitation skills;
4. apply group concepts and skills to relevant settings

(Individual course teachers may update the learning outcome as and whenever necessary.)

1. Acquire a repertoire of basic communication skills that is essential to counselling;
2. Develop an understanding of the counselling process;
3. Apply counselling skills in the helping process and reflect on the appropriateness of the skills used;
4. Demonstrate an understanding of the ethical principles of the counselling profession.

(Individual course teachers may update the learning outcome as and whenever necessary.)

1. demonstrate basic understanding of assessment and conceptualization for different presenting problems;
2. develop counseling goals and plans that are relevant to the conceptualization;
3. integrate counseling strategies that would be pertinent to the needs of clients; and
4. reflect on countertransference concerning the work with different client issues and understand the basics of countertransference management.

(Individual course teachers may update the learning outcome as and whenever necessary.)

